Pre-words ¶

Motivation ¶

In the mid of 2020, I wanted to buy a new second hand car to replace my old one. And at that time, my ideal type was BMW. After I roughly surfed on several car dealer portals, more and more questions came to my mind, for example,

  • what are the key points to a price, e.g. how long the car has been produced and used, or the horsepower?
  • does auto-gear cost more than manual? if, yes, roughly how much. Is there still many manual car?
  • do manufacturer-authorized dealer require higher prices?
  • ...and much more

Since two years I began to leanr data science and am curious if what I have learned can give an overview to this puzzle.

Data Source ¶

The data used in this project were scraped in the last two weeks of July 2020, from a online protal based in Germany and provided EU-wide. These data are not used for business purposes, but only for my research.

The total amount of my data is ca. 55000. I will only used BMW 1er data (ca. 8500) for this project.
Data only range those cars first-registered from Jan 2010.

Tools and skill ¶

In this project, I will demo how I handle data with

  1. regular expression
  2. data visualization skill
  3. natual language process (NLP)
  4. application of machine learning

Data wrangling ¶

Data wrangling requires a big effort and a relatively complex process. Therefore I will not get into details here.
The targets of my data wrangling here are:

  1. fill missing data by probability (e.g. finding similar data and calculate which is most possible)
  2. convert data type, for example, register date from string to time-stamp, which can be more widely used in visualization
  3. convert tags/tokens into lists or dicts for NLP
  4. remove data missing too much information

Here are the explaination of each feature

  1. series (str): 1er, 2er,... here only 1er is selected out, thus all are "1"
  2. model (str): 114, 116, 118,...
  3. price (int): price in EUR
  4. condition (str): Neu (new), Jahreswagen (year car), Gebraucht (used),...
  5. gear_type (str): manual or automatic
  6. fuel_type (str): Benzin (petrol) or Diesel
  7. mileage (int): mileage in km
  8. first_reg (str): month/year of when the car firstly registered
  9. age_mon (int): age in month derived from first_reg
  10. power_ps (int): horsepower
  11. owner (int): how many pre-owner (-1 means unknown)
  12. guarantee_months (int/obj): either be int (how many months guarantee) or be str (Yes means yes but don't know how long)
  13. smoke-free (int): yes (1) and no (0)
  14. next_HU (int): when to next inspection, in month
  15. full_service_history (int): yes (1) and no (0)
  16. drive_type (int): rear/front/4wd or unknown
  17. eng_disp (int): engine displacement
  18. doors (int): number of doors (-1 means unknown)
  19. ext_color (list of str): ['black'], ['white', 'blue'] for example
  20. int_color (list of str): ['black'], ['white', 'blue'] for example
  21. body (str): limousine, coupe,...
  22. country_ver (str): country version, such as de, nl, fr, eu,...
  23. seats (int): number of seats (-1 means unknown)
  24. emission (int): emission
  25. particulate_sticker (str): 1,3,4,5 (-1 means unknown)
  26. consume (_combine, _in_town, _out_of_town) (float): fuel consumation
  27. seller (str): the seller names if they are resellers, otherwise private
  28. postcode (str): where they sell
  29. city (str): where they sell
  30. reviews (int): how many reviews they got, especially for resellers. Private seller will be -1
  31. kw_comfort (list of str): keywords of comfort equipment
  32. kw_extras (list of str): keywords of extra equipment
  33. kw_media (list of str): keywords of media equipment
  34. kw_safety (list of str): keywords of safety equipment
  35. tags (list of str): tags
  36. description (str): the text seller left in the text field

Price prediction ¶

in this section, I would like to explore key factors of a second-hand car price. Here I will

  1. observe the model by correlation and data visualization
  2. establish a model for price based on mathematical approach
  3. improve the accuracy of price prediction
  4. use the mathematical approach improving machine learning model
  5. bring out an idea of price recommendation system

Exploration ¶

In order to know which factors have the most influence on price, the best way could be the correlation.
Let's just select them out for price:

Here, from both positive and negative side, we can see the most crucial categories are

  1. age_mon (age): how many months since first registration
  2. mileage: the mileage
  3. power_ps: horsepower

It is intuitive that the age_mon should be highly related to mileage, as the longer since the car registered the more mileage it could have.
Let's have a look on their correlation.

correlation of months and mileage: 0.697870428320367

Since the age_mon has larger correlation on price, I will choose this for the first exploration and would compensate the influence of mileage later.

Price model based on age ¶

As said, only the cars register firstly from Jan 2010 were scraped, thus the maximum of time is 126 months.

In a reasonable way, I will establish a exponential model for fitting price and the number of months, because in most cases, price decreases by time and it will never go beneath zero (you will not sell car by paying yourself).

Define the fit-model and its plot function then we can obtain the fit curve.

fitting: price = 29086.245764018116 * exp(-0.011406846543436674 * months)

We have to evaluate how good this model is. The first step is to check the distribution of price.

And the plot: actual price vs fitted (predicted) by the exponential model

It does not look very well and makes sense as we have not considered the other key factor horsepower yet.


On the other hand, distribution sometimes will not tell exactly the deviation in a datum, it only tells the entire tendence.
Therefore I am introducing root mean squared error (RMSE) for evaluating the performance.

Let's have a first view of thess criterions.

5120 EUR, the root mean squared error between price and prediction

Here I would like to show how these error distribute on car models, as it could highly relate to the horsepower.

This looks somehow reasonable since the deviation varies with the car model when the other factors are not introduced yet, i.e. the more right side models, the more horsepower they have.
I will then include horsepower to improve this price prediction model.

At first step, I would like to shortly check if the price between the horsepower significantly recognizible/distinguishable by

  1. spliting data into 3 bins - low, medium and high
  2. check their ANOVA by each other

Since the F-values are very high and P-values are very close to 0, in 95% level of significance, null hypothesis is rejected. Horsepower is assumed having a significance on price.

Following we can check again how does it look like when we add color map on the previous price-months plot.

This plot makes the overview in a clearer way.

Here I slightly change the evaluation criterions by removing the absolute operator, in order to know the linearity and correlation between horsepower and the error/differences.

Out[27]:
power_ps rmse
power_ps 1.000000 0.708129
rmse 0.708129 1.000000

From my point of view, this correlation is absolutely significant. Thus, a linear-fit for horsepower will be attempted here.

Define a new fit-curve function, we can obtain a new prediction model, the predict price below

fitting: price = (106.03450733771027*hp + 11846.346256374409) * exp(-0.01061590913617442 * months)

(it was - price = 29086.245764018116 exp(-0.011406846543436674 months))

By the same concept, the criterions for evaluating deviation can also be modified like below:

3751 EUR, the root mean squared error between price and prediction

This also reflects in the chart.

Hint for hidden cell: process done!

We can see, by considering the horsepower, the RMSE of the models on the right side decreased significantly. Now they have the similar RMSE level compared to the models left side who have less horsepower. Compensating horsepower does really work.

1er M Coup is a special model. Even though the horsepower has been considered, its prices still have obvious error.
Same phenomenon below in the plot.

1er M Coup is an old model and has a special appearance compared to the current style. It could be the key factor that they are being sold with much higher price. We will look more into details for 1er M Coup later.

And even the distribution has a significant improvement.

This looks much better, but still far from good. Thus, I will introduce machine learning regression for price prediction.

Price predict - regression by machine learning with NLP ¶

We have created a price prediction model by the age and horsepower, nevertheless there are still some factors, which are not so influential as age and horsepower, but very helpful for us to enhance the performance.

For example, 1er M Coup has the same horsepower as 140, which means, if they also have the same age, we will not able to tell the difference of their prices, contradicted to what we've seen, that 1er M Coup always has a better price. In that way, if we could take category 'model' into account and then the '1er M Coup' will be a variance of the price, it could help improving the price prediction model.

For these cases, the following tasks will be done in this section:

  1. convert data from string to boolean or one-hot to integers for some categories having only few or fixed options, e.g.
    {'gear_type': 'automatic', 'manual'} --> {'automatic': True, False}
    {'condition':'Gebracht', 'Jahreswagen', 'Vorfhrfahrzeug', 'Tageszulassung', 'Neu'} --> {'condition': 0, 1, 2, 3, 4}
  2. scalarize categories with wide range of integer of fload
  3. vectorize categories with tags or text or tokens
  4. wrangle data as above as input, and the error (difference in price) as output, then split them into train and test sets
  5. create pipeline and grid search for tuning/traning machine learning model

Feature Engineering ¶

The target here is to numerize features so that they can be used in machine learning model.
Steps:

  1. remove features which have too many -1 (unknown) or 'unknown' value, such as 'particulate_sticker', 'consume_in_town', 'consume_out_of_town', 'reviews', 'country_ver',
  2. remove the instances having -1 as unknown in a few features, such as 'owner', 'doors', 'seats', 'emission', 'consume_combine'
  3. onehot for categorized features, such as 'model', 'condition', 'gear_type', 'fuel_type', 'drive_type', 'ext_color', 'body', 'emission_class'
  4. onehot for categorized lists, such as 'int_color', 'kw_comfort', 'kw_extras', 'kw_media', 'kw_safety', 'tags'
  5. scalarize numerical features, such as 'consume_combine', 'mileage', 'emission', 'mileage', 'emission', 'age_mon', 'power_ps', 'owner', 'next_HU', 'eng_disp', 'doors', 'seats'
  6. vectorized by tfidf for description, in order to get tokens and distributions
  7. remove not needed features, such as 'series','guarantee_months', 'postcode', 'city', 'first_reg', 'seller'

Here I will choose the following 22 columns/categories for machine learning model,

  • power_ps, mileage, age_mon: scalarized and seen as compensation of our previos model
  • next_HU: scalarized how long till next official examination
  • automatic, Diesel, private_seller: binarized from gear_type, fuel_type and vendor(private/dealer)
  • condition_onehotted: from {'Gebracht', 'Jahreswagen', 'Vorfhrfahrzeug', 'Tageszulassung', 'Neu'} to {0, 1, 2, 3, 4}
  • guarantee_binarized, smoke-free, full_service_history: from Yes/No to True/False
  • owner, doors: kept same
  • consume_combine: scalarized
  • model, kw_comfort, kw_extras, kw_media, kw_safety, tags, ext_color, description: vectorized for tags/tokens/words

And clean out the data which miss these info.

First step, scalarize numerical features (which have been binarized will not be included).
Considering the data distribution, different features will adopt different scalers

Summary ¶

This price prediction model can be seen a prework of price recommendation system. What make this model different is that the model was not totally built by machine learning - it contains a reasonable mathematical model, i.e. the exponential, which lead a slightly better performance.

Future work ¶

  1. Considering the coefficients of the lasso regressor, the features might be able to provide more insight. for example, which reseller use "vorbehaltlich" or "sichtbar" for their description as format and are selling more expensive cars.
  2. The information are getting lost when/if the seller input them manually. In practice, the online marketplace can obtain the seiries number (FIN) of the car. This will make the information more complete so that the error is expected to minimized.
  3. Overfitting is frequently a problem. It could have appeared in this research since the gridsearch score is lower than train/test score. It could be tried again with setting refit=False, and furthermore, standarize/scalarize more in my data and lessen the token could help.

Insight from age of the car ¶

In this section, I will try to find some insight solely from the age of the used car selling on the marktplace.

Exploration ¶

At the first step, let's have a quick look to the histogram of the amount to different age range.

What remarkable here are,

  1. the peak locates the range of age 36-42 months
  2. a smaller peak in the range 12-18 months

But why these? Does it relate to certain car models?
Or, does it imply a special sales-mode, that people sell their car shortly after 3 years or 1 year?
What can we extract from our data?

Relation between ages and models ¶

For being able to have proper scale for y-axis of following plots, define the plot function here first. Then we can plot the histogram: amount to age for each 1er model.

The amounts distribute differently by the model.

But we have to keep in mind, that these only mean "used cars selling currently", not implies "How many 1er of each model were produced/sold by BMW".
We should not confuse them and hence, no inference of which were sold more/better by BMW. For example, the peak in 36-42 months cannot certainly be intepreted as BMW produced more in this time frame - more prodution could lead this result but could not be a certainty.

Nevertheless, anyway, we are still able to see that some models seem to be stopped for production and some are new types or new generations.

The following data for BMW 1er generations and its production times can be found on Wikipedia.
For a better overview, I added this info on the plot.

This looks very cool and understandable.
The amounts can roughly match and reflect the generation data.
And, furthermore, some findings:

  1. for some models, they have new generation and somehow corresponds to the peak of 12-18 range, e.g. 118 & 135. But not 100% certainty, for example, 116, 120 and 140 not.
  2. Generation cannot somehow explain the peak 12-18, but not the 36-42.

Nevertheless, the peak 12-18 appear for new models let me think of promotion for new generation.
When it comes to promotion or sales-mode, we should have a look into the vendor, because the private seller cannot provide this promotion as dealers do.

New promotion ways hide behind - leasing ¶

For the first step, a sub dataframe will be selected out, so that we can seperate the age, condition, and seller type from the entire, in order to see the difference among the age ranges.

Future work ¶
